Korrus is a rapidly growing technology company focused on a new field of study, Human Light Interaction. We seek to understand human interactions with light and create technologies that enable rapid innovation, limitless variation, and future-proof adaptation. Through our patented spectral recipes, artificial intelligence and software-defined infrastructure, we develop, implement and optimize light technologies to improve the physiological, visual, and psychological well-being of humans. 
Our strategy is audacious, and our expectations are high. We are pioneering in the areas of color science, AI and machine learning and software defined light. Using the sun as inspiration, we are using our inventions to enhance the worldâ€™s understanding of light and materially transform expectations for artificial light. 
Korrus hires curious, collaborative, autonomous and smart people who also happen to be very nice. We have a passion for tackling the unknown, solving hard problems, and answering questions that havenâ€™t been explored. 
Primary Role and Responsibility 
The Sr. Director of Operations is the strategic leader across all NPI, manufacturing engineering, estimating, procurement, supply chain, logistics, quality, and worldwide manufacturing operations. Reporting directly to the VP of Operations, the Sr. Director of Operations provides strategic and tactical direction of the operations team in line with our mission, vision, values, strategic plan, and financial objectives. 
In this role, the individual oversees and directs all operations while delivering best practices in lean manufacturing and strategic sourcing in ways that grow revenue, profitability and product quality. The Sr. Director of Operations provides guidance and leadership to improve efficiency and effectiveness of the existing production operations, and is fully responsible for its technical and commercial operations. 
 
Streamline workflow and create a team environment to increase productivity 
 Optimize of inventory networks, plant line capacity, processing planning capabilities and systems 
 Participate in strategic planning activities. 
 Identify capability and/or capacity gaps in existing staffing, equipment, and processes 
 Propose solutions to support the strategic initiatives, including timing, cost, and ROI (when applicable) 
 Collaborate to develop capital budget requirements, and manage the costs of manufacturing, including labor, equipment expenses and capital 
 Contribute to the annual budget and determines operational expenditures and then manages the budget and cost controls in overall operations 
 Ensures alignment of processes and resolves operational conflicts 
 Review and modify existing equipment and production methods to reduce costs and improve quality. 
 Develop and implement effective quality control programs to ensure that quality standards and objectives are met. 
 Direct manufacturing operations through establishment and implementation of best-practice policies and procedures 
 Take a strategic view of the organization and facilitates the creation of a company-wide culture and use methodologies to drive core/strategic processes to respond to the needs of customers with minimal waste. 
 Provide leadership/mentoring/training to all levels of the organization on the use, practice, and implementation strategy of Lean methodology and tools. 
 Drive effective on-going communications throughout the organization on the implementation of lean thinking to help drive culture change and advance lean competencies; provide clear and regular communication regarding the LPCâ€™s goals and objectives of the lean thinking and to provide a system for measurement of results of lean activities on an ongoing basis. 
 Gathers and prioritizes projects and allocate resources according to diverse criteria such as strategic importance, cost/benefit, likelihood of success, stakeholder engagement. 
